result.execSummary:
The defendant Jabril Harris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must obtain his GED.

The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 5 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.
The defendant may not possess or consume alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns.
The defendant must submit a DNA sample.
The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Jabril Harris in court with attorney Chad Lynch.  Defendant Jabril Harris in custody.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:16 PM. Lynch - resolved - provides court with plea questionnaire - plead to count #1 as alleged, #2 as alleged and DRI #3, #2 - 90 days jail, 2 years probation, imposed and stayed sentence of 9 months, $100 fine on both counts, #1 - 90 imposed and stayed - consecutive to count #2 if revoked. Court dismisses and reads in count #3. Harris plead NC to count #1 and pleads G to count #2. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Lynch makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - asks for jail time to be served in Milwaukee County. Harris makes statement, remorseful. Court sentences the defendant to the following: count #1 - impose 90 days in FC jail - consecutive to I&S time on count #2, stayed - place on probation for 2 years, concurrent to count #1, with conditions of: costs - paid thru probation, AODA and follow thru, maintain employment/school (5 jobs), no consumption of possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, 50 hours of community service, obtain GED; count #2 - impose 9 months in FC jail - stayed, place on for 2 years with conditions of: 90 days conditional jail - huber allowed - eligible for community service under 973.03(3) - consecutive to jail time on count #2 if revoked - credit for 19 days if revoked, costs - paid thru probation, same conditions as count #1 except no additional community service, submit DNA sample - defense counsel objects to surcharge, right to appeal, adjourned.
No consumption of alcohol and no contact with victim unless proper paperwork has been signed.

Defendant Jabril Harris in court with attorney Chad Lynch.  Defendant Jabril Harris in custody and appears via video from FOSO.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 1:24 PM. Lynch and Harris has complaint, has gone over the complaint, waives reading, enters NG pleas. Court accepts pleas, will set for FPT. Lynch and State want to address bond - prefers signature bond but if cash, asking for $250.00 cash. State - bond - no objections to signature bond and believes a no contact waiver has been approved/signed. Court - bond - $2000.000 signature bond, no consumption of alcohol and no contact with victim unless the waiver has been signed.  Final pre-trial scheduled for January 20, 2016 at 01:45 pm.
No contact with victim (JR). No consumption of alcohol.
